    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "interesting. so you're saying it was a failure because of the instability? but some people argue that the failure wasn't the intervention itself, but just the lack of follow-through or \"nation building\" afterwards. like, if we had stayed and actually built up the institutions, wouldn't that have changed the outcome? or is the whole idea of interventionism just fundamentally flawed?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The argument that the failure lies in the lack of post-intervention nation-building is a sophisticated way of pointing out the inherent weakness of purely military action. Proponents of this view argue that intervention without a comprehensive strategy for state-building is inherently doomed to fail. However, the fundamental flaw in interventionism is often the assumption that external powers can impose stability on deeply rooted local conflicts. The Libyan case proves that external military force can address immediate crises but cannot solve complex, internal political problems.",
      "source": "target",
